Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
saveTimingBudget(25.10)                                saveTimingBudget(25.10)

Name
       saveTimingBudget  -  Saves  the  previously derived timing budgets to a
       specified directory

Syntax
       saveTimingBudget

       [-help]

       [-dir <dirName>]

       [{<instList>}]

       [-inst <string> | -ptn <string>]

       [-module_model_tag <string>]

       Saves the previously derived timing budgets to a  specified  directory.
       The main outputs of this command are the block constraints and the tim-
       ing model. In the MMMC mode, the saveTimingBudget outputs the block and
       top viewdefinition.tcl as well.

       Use  this  command after deriving the time budgets using the deriveTim-
       ingBudget command.

       Note: The software will not write PG information while using the  save-
       TimingBudget  command. To get accurate PG information in the partition-
       block .lib, run the following commands in sequence:

       partition

       savePartition

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each saveTimingBudget parameter.

              For  a  detailed  description of the command and all its parame-
              ters, use the man command: man saveTimingBudget

       <instList>
              Saves the budget files for instances.  You  use  this  parameter
              with the deriveTimingBudget -inst command.

       -dir <dirName>
              Specifies  the  relative directory name where the derived timing
              budget files will be saved. These files are saved in  a  sub-di-
              rectory     named    cellName_timingViewName.sdc.gz    at    the
              dirName/cellName/cellName_timingViewName.sdc.gz location through
              the relative directory path. If you do not specify this  parame-
              ter, the timing budget files are saved in the current directory.
              For example, if you run the following command, a directory named
              STB will be saved at the current path:

              deriveTimingBudget -dir STB

       -inst <instList>| -ptn <ptnList >
              Saves  the budget file for partitions or instances for which you
              have generated timing budgets. You do not need to  specify  -ptn
              or  -inst  if  you  have previously specified deriveTimingBudget
              -ilm.

              The -ptn parameter saves the budget files  for  partitions.  You
              use this parameter with the deriveTimingBudget -ptn command.

              The  -inst  parameter  saves the budget files for instances. You
              use this parameter with the deriveTimingBudget -inst command.

              Default: The tool saves budgets for all instances and partitions
              specified by deriveTimingBudget.

       -module_model_tag <string>
              Creates a new mmmc directory and  saves  the  view  definitions,
              libs,  and  constraints therein. The created mmmc directory will
              be located as follows:

              <shdb_root>/<block_name>/<tag_name>/mmmc

              For example:

              * The saveTimingBudget -module_model_tag ABCD command will  save
                view    definition,   libs,   and   constraints   within   the
                shdb_root/block_name/ABCD/mmmc directory.

              * The default behavior of  the  savePartition  -module_model_tag
                ABCD  command  is not impacted, and the view definition, libs,
                and constraints are saved in  the  .enc.dat  file  within  the
                shdb_root/block_name/ABCD/pnr directory.

              * The  saveTimingBudget -module_model_tag ABCD and savePartition
                -module_model_tag ABCD  commands  are  completely  independent
                (those will not affect the functioning of each other).

Examples
       The following examples are based on a scenario, where a design with the
       ptn1 partition has two instances, L1 as the master, and L1_clone as the
       clone:

              * The  following  set  of commands saves the timing budget files
                for partition in the STB/ptn1 directory. It saves  the  timing
                budget information for both the partition and top. Also, since
                it  uses the masterOnly mode, the budgets will be based on the
                master timing only:

                deriveTimingBudget -ptn ptn1

                saveTimingBudget -dir STB

              * The following set of commands saves timing budget  files  only
                for  the L1_clone instance in the STB/ptn1 directory. Since it
                uses the merged mode, the timing budgeting information will be
                based on the worst case data from both the instances. In  this
                case,  any  of  the master or clone instances, or both, can be
                specified while running saveTimingBudget. The best approach is
                to not specify either of those, and let  the  saveTimingBudget
                command save the information generated by the deriveTimingBud-
                get command:

                setBudgetingMode -masterClone merged

                deriveTimingBudget -inst {L1 L1_clone}

                saveTimingBudget -dir STB -inst {L1_clone}

              * The  following  set  of commands saves the timing budget files
                for the L1 instance in the STB/ptn1 directory.  It  saves  the
                timing budget information for only the partition instance:

                deriveTimingBudget -inst L1 (or L1_clone)

                saveTimingBudget -dir STB

              * The  following  set  of commands saves the timing budget files
                for the L1 instance in the STB/ptn1.L1 directory, and for  the
                L1_clone instance in the STB/ptn1.L1_clone directory. It saves
                the  timing  budget  information  only  for  the partition in-
                stances:

                deriveTimingBudget -inst {L1 L1_clone}

                saveTimingBudget -dir STB

              * The following set of commands saves the  timing  budget  files
                only for the L1_clone instance in the STB/ptn1.L1_clone direc-
                tory:

                deriveTimingBudget -inst {L1 L1_clone}

                saveTimingBudget -dir STB -inst {L1_clone}

